Although initiatives to rectify the deficiency of underrepresented minorities in STEM disciplines have increased diversity at the undergraduate level, it has not translated to diversity in engineering academia. The overarching goal of the proposed project was to provide year-long professional training to better prepare participants for a successful career as engineering professors. Several sub-goals have been identified to assist with the realization of the overall goal:

1. Increase the awareness of what is "needed" to be a successful assistant professor;
 2. Quantify the specific areas Ph.D. students and post-docs need the most assistance with;
 3. Increase participant knowledge of effective STEM undergraduate teaching and learning;
 4. Advance awareness and skills pertaining to (a) curriculum development, (b) lecture delivery, and (c) assessment;
 5. Assist with enhancing the establishment of a research career ? (a) initial writing (proposal, papers), (b) how to address reviewer's comment, (c) budget development; and
 6. Increase the networking opportunities for participants.

The goals of this proposed project were achieved by conducting a two-week intensive professional preparation course in conjunction with year-long activities of practical hands-on training in the areas of teaching, service, and research.  Participants were provided opportunities to write a travel proposal to receive funds to meet with a federal grant program director or attend a technical conference.  Each year the approach was implemented and hosted at one of the collaborating institutions with participants (doctoral students or postdoctoral fellows) recruited from the host university, institutions within three hours of the host institution, as well as four participants from the collaborating institutions.  The program started at The University of Akron in the summer of 2017 with the first cohort of 13 fellows. The second cohort included 26 fellows and was conducted in the summer of 2018 at The University of Houston. The third cohort was conducted at Mississippi State University in the summer of 2019 and recruited 23 fellows. The activities with the third cohort concluded in May 2020. A follow-up survey was sent to the three cohorts to evaluate the impact of the program on fellows from one to three years after completing the program. The program was completed with more than 15 fellows becoming assistant professors in different engineering disciplines. In the final survey, the participants agreed or strongly agreed that the program prepared them for the responsibilities and expectations to succeed in academic positions (92% and 97% respectively). These results demonstrated that the project was completed successfully.



